# Code Style

## Comments
- No comments unless code genuinely can't explain itself (regex, non-obvious math, API quirks)
- A good name beats any comment

## Naming
- Intention-revealing, entity-based: `userForm`, `invoiceList`, `db`, `env`
- Allowed abbreviations: `db`, `ctx`, `req`, `res`, `err`, `tmp`, `cfg`, `id`
- No abbreviations that need decoding: never `uFrm`, `invLst`, `itmRndr`
- Booleans: `isLoading`, `hasError`, `canSubmit`

## Simplicity
- Write the simplest correct solution — flat over nested, explicit over clever
- Optimize for a new team member reading it in 5 seconds

## Extensibility
- Repeat once, abstract on second duplication — no premature abstraction
- No config flags, options, or generics for hypothetical future use cases

# Tradeoff Interruption Rule (Strict)
When a task involves a genuine tradeoff (hard-code vs. config, inline vs. hook, single component vs. composable API) — **stop and ask**. State the tradeoff in one sentence, present two options. Never silently pick one.

> Example: "This can be a single `<Card />` with props (simpler) or `<Card.Root><Card.Header /></Card.Root>` (composable). Which do you prefer?"

# UI — Radix Composition
- Small focused primitives, not monolithic components with many props
- Always use compound pattern: `<Dialog.Root>`, `<Dialog.Trigger>`, `<Dialog.Content>`
- Always spread props onto the underlying DOM node
- Use `asChild` when the caller decides the element type
- Components own behavior and accessibility — callers own styling
- Never add a prop to control what composition already handles